Ukraine on the way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," said Rudyard Kipling once.
The Ukraine is indeed in the east, but in the east of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path there was not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a Social Democrat and was never a member of the Communist Party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It goes without saying that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine has had in joining Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural production areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We completely messed up the reform.
For often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West—private property, free market economy, strict respect for human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy—in a diluted form, and believed that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) over the years has adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is somewhat like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has now gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
One can see this on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers allow pedestrians to cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to cross the street in safety despite reckless drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a vibrant café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the internet in internet cafes.
But these are merely the whimsical musings of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, there has been a development from a total rejection of reforms, through a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption, to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
At first, the reform of the state provoked a hostile sentiment among both bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of public service employees began.
It was a "F-style" reform: the state must shrink, people assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about the fact that countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
For the problem is not only a matter of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily improve simply because we apply the red pen, led us to the second stage of our reform process.
Slowly, the state was reformed in a more sophisticated manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
This stabilized the work of the government ministries.
At first, the authority entrusted to these new areas was too broad, making it difficult to carry out their work effectively.
Now they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (even though reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of whom there are still too many among us - can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
The taming of our radicals and the radical impulse was not simple.
Why?
Ukraine was for too long a province of the USSR and of the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
That has shaped our mentality. Because radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial person cannot possibly admit their own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians had to realize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have ourselves contributed to becoming even more ill, but the recent elections, which have undermined the Communists' dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalized individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous journey to Europe helped a weak new nation to become strong and survive.
